n Europe and the Americas, colonialism in Africa, and the nuclear threat at the start of the Cold War. In analyzing their work, Garcia traces how such attempts to link black music and dance to Africa unintentionally reinforced the binary relationships between the West and Africa, white and black, the modern and the primitive, science and magic, and rural and urban. It was, Garcia demonstrates, modernity's determinations of unraced, heteronormative, and productive bodies, and of scientific truth that helped defer the realization of individual and political freedom in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aBlacksxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aDance musicxHistory and criticism. 0aDance, Black. 0aMusicxAfrican influencesxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczAfricaxHistory and criticism. 4aAlan Merriam Book Award winners. 4aBritish Forum for Ethnomusicology book award winners. 4aBruno Nettl book award winners. 4aSociety for Ethnomusicology book awards. 4aethnomusicology book awards. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373117zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373117.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles